**Step 2: Download and install BigMemory MAX\
(Used for Master Server 2 and Lobby3)**

Go to <http://terracotta.org/products/bigmemory> and click “Free
Download” under the column “BigMemory Max”

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,){width="623"
height="601"}

If done correctly, you should have a directory on your harddrive similar
to C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1 . MasterServer2 has been build with 4.0.1, so
you will need this specific version. You should also get an email
containing a file ‘terracotta-license.key’. Save this file to
"C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\terracotta-license.key" The server will look
for it here on startup.

Edit start-tc-server.bat

Open "C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin\\start-tc-server.bat" and
find this line:

set JAVA\_OPTS=%OPTS% %JAVA\_OPTS%

Change it to

set JAVA\_OPTS=%OPTS% %JAVA\_OPTS% -Xms1024m -Xmx1024m
-XX:MaxDirectMemorySize=8448m

Create and paste tc-config.xml

Go to C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin and create a file
tc-config.xml

If your server has 8 GB of RAM, paste these contents

&lt;!--All content copyright (c) 2003-2008 Terracotta, Inc.,\
except as may otherwise be noted in a separate copyright notice.\
All rights reserved--&gt;

&lt;!--This config file is used by the server and bootjar tool when none
is specified.--&gt;\
&lt;tc:tc-config xmlns:tc="http://www.terracotta.org/config"&gt;\
&lt;servers&gt;\
&lt;server&gt;\
&lt;offheap&gt;\
&lt;enabled&gt;true&lt;/enabled&gt;\
&lt;maxDataSize&gt;1.5G&lt;/maxDataSize&gt;\
&lt;/offheap&gt;\
&lt;data&gt;%(user.home)/terracotta/4.0.1/server-data&lt;/data&gt;\
&lt;logs&gt;%(user.home)/terracotta/4.0.1/server-logs&lt;/logs&gt;\
&lt;/server&gt;\
&lt;restartable enabled="true"/&gt;\
&lt;/servers&gt;\
&lt;clients&gt;\
&lt;logs&gt;%(user.home)/terracotta/4.0.1/client-logs&lt;/logs&gt;\
&lt;/clients&gt;\
&lt;/tc:tc-config&gt;

If your server has 16 GB of RAM or higher, paste these contents

&lt;!--All content copyright (c) 2003-2008 Terracotta, Inc.,\
except as may otherwise be noted in a separate copyright notice.\
All rights reserved--&gt;

&lt;!--This config file is used by the server and bootjar tool when none
is specified.--&gt;\
&lt;tc:tc-config xmlns:tc="http://www.terracotta.org/config"&gt;\
&lt;servers&gt;\
&lt;server&gt;\
&lt;offheap&gt;\
&lt;enabled&gt;true&lt;/enabled&gt;\
&lt;maxDataSize&gt;8G&lt;/maxDataSize&gt;\
&lt;/offheap&gt;\
&lt;data&gt;%(user.home)/terracotta/4.0.1/server-data&lt;/data&gt;\
&lt;logs&gt;%(user.home)/terracotta/4.0.1/server-logs&lt;/logs&gt;\
&lt;/server&gt;\
&lt;restartable enabled="true"/&gt;\
&lt;/servers&gt;\
&lt;clients&gt;\
&lt;logs&gt;%(user.home)/terracotta/4.0.1/client-logs&lt;/logs&gt;\
&lt;/clients&gt;\
&lt;/tc:tc-config&gt;

**Step 6: Setup Apache Tomcat\
(Used for Master Server 2 and Lobby3)**

Apache Tomcat setup is confusing, so follow these instructions
carefully. Also, note that Apache Tomcat and Apache are different things
and nowhere is this really explained, which confused me for many days.
If you run into problems, be careful to search for “Tomcat” and not
Apache.

Add an environment variable CATALINA\_HOME

Set CATALINA\_HOME to where you unzipped Apache Tomcat, for example
C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39 . This is important or else your webpage will
not show up later for what seems to be inexplicable reasons.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,){width="526"
height="582"}

(Apache Tomcat sometimes refers to itself as Catalina)

\
\

Open the file "C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\conf\\server.xml" in a text
editor

This file contains most (but not all) of the setting related to your
webpage deployment. Find the block that looks like this:

&lt;Host name="localhost" appBase="webapps"

unpackWARs="true" autoDeploy="true"&gt;

The &lt;Host …&gt; block tells Apache Tomcat where to find your
webpage(s) on the harddrive.

Set your &lt;Host&gt; block to your domain

&lt;Host name="www.masterserver2.raknet.com"
appBase="RakNet/masterserver2" unpackWARs="true" autoDeploy="true"&gt;

If you want more than one domain for the same website, you can use
&lt;Alias&gt; such as

&lt;Host name="www.masterserver2.raknet.com"
appBase="RakNet/masterserver2" unpackWARs="true" autoDeploy="true"&gt;

&lt;Alias&gt;masterserver2.raknet.com&lt;/Alias&gt;

&lt;Alias&gt;mygame.masterserver2.raknet.com&lt;/Alias&gt;

&lt;/Host&gt;

If you want to set an error page for direct IP address, also add this
line:

&lt;Host name="localhost" appBase="webapps/error" unpackWARs="true"
autoDeploy="true"&gt; &lt;/Host&gt;

Then have a file
"C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\webapps\\error\\ROOT\\index.html" where
index.html contains an error message.

Otherwise, you can point it to either Lobby 3 or Master Server 2

&lt;Host appBase=="RakNet/masterserver2" autoDeploy="true"
name="localhost" unpackWARs="true"&gt;

Change your webpage port from 8080 to 80

&lt;Connector port="8080" protocol="HTTP/1.1"

connectionTimeout="20000"

redirectPort="8443" /&gt;

To

&lt;Connector port="80" protocol="HTTP/1.1"

connectionTimeout="20000"

redirectPort="443" /&gt;

Port 80 is the default port webbrowsers use to find your webpage. If you
leave it at 8080, then you would have to access the url with :8080 at
the end, such as www.masterserver2.raknet.com:8080

Increase the memory given to Apache Tomcat

Next, you will need to increase the amount of memory given to Apache
Tomcat, in this case 2.5 GB. How to set Apache Tomcat environment
variables is difficult to figure out, due to conflicting and wrong
information on the web about how to do it.

The correct way on Windows:

Go to C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\bin or equivalent, and add a file
setenv.bat . Paste this into the contents of the file:

set CATALINA\_OPTS=-Xms2560m -Xmx2560m
-Dcom.tc.tc.config.total.timeout=5000

Place and unzip ROOT.war so Apache Tomcat can find it

You will be provided a ROOT.war for Master Server 2, and another for
Lobby3. For Lobby3, place it at
"C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\lobby3\\ROOT.war". Delete any other
files at that location. For Master Server 2, place it at
"C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\masterserver2\\ROOT.war". Delete any
other files at that location.

Next, unzip ROOT.war using 7-zip ( <http://www.7-zip.org/> ), or an
alternative

If done correctly, you will have a file
"C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\lobby3\\ROOT.war" In that same
directory, you will have a directory
"C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\lobby3\\ROOT". In
"C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\lobby3\\ROOT" you should have
index.html and numerous other files.

Copy BigMemory license file

Find "C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\terracotta-license.key"

MasterServer2: Copy it to
C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\masterserver2\\ROOT\\WEB-INF\\classes\
Lobby3: Copy it to
C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\lobby3\\ROOT\\WEB-INF\\classes

Copy GeoIP database file

Find ‘GeoIPCity.dat’ you saved in step 3. The location to place it is
the same as the BigMemory license files

MasterServer2: Copy it to
C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\masterserver2\\ROOT\\WEB-INF\\classes\
Lobby3: Copy it to
C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\RakNet\\lobby3\\ROOT\\WEB-INF\\classes

**Step 7: Setup SSL\
(Used for Lobby3 only)**

SSL is not necessary for MasterServer 2. It is necessary for Lobby3, and
if you use Lobby3 on the same server you will need to follow these steps
at some point.

To use SSL, you can use a self-signed key or you can purchase a key from
a certificate authority. A self-signed key can be used for testing,
before you spend money buying an SSL certificate.

Get the Tomcat Native Connector

Go to
<http://apache.mirrors.lucidnetworks.net/tomcat/tomcat-connectors/native/1.1.27/binaries/>
and download tomcat-native-1.1.27-win32-bin.zip . This is the ‘Tomcat
Native Connector’ which is faster for SSL and enables APR, or something
like that. All I know it the system inexplicably won’t work without it.

In the zip, find bin/x64/tcnative-1.dll. tcnative-1.dll is in the zip
file three times, so use this exact one. I’m not sure what the other two
are for, or what the difference is, except they do not work. Copy
tcnative-1.dll to C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.37\\bin or your equivalent.

(Option 1) Get a self-signed key

Go here\
<http://www.selfsignedcertificate.com/>

Enter your web address, press generate, download the .key and .cert
files, and put them in a new directory
C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\conf\\raknet (you can rename raknet to
something else if desired).

(Option 2) Get an SSL certificate from a certificate authority

I ordered an SSL certificate from [<span
style="text-decoration: none">http://www.rapidssl.com/</span>](http://www.rapidssl.com/)
although there are many ssl certificate vendors to order from. There are
a lot of unnecessary options they try to sell you, just ignore that and
do whatever is cheapest, except possibly for the validity period. You
should set that for as many years as you need the certificate.

After you order the certificate, you will get an email asking you to
confirm it.

Once the certificate is confirmed, you will need the public,
intermediate, and private keys. I had to specifically ask for this by
email, once the certificate was confirmed. I was given 3 files,
intermediate.txt, lobby3.raknet.com.txt, privatekey.txt

Setup SSL connectors:

Open "C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.37\\conf\\server.xml" again, and find this
block of code you edited earlier:

&lt;Connector port="80" protocol="HTTP/1.1"

connectionTimeout="20000"

redirectPort="443" /&gt;

Immediately after that block, add something similar to this:

&lt;Connector port="443"
protocol="org.apache.coyote.http11.Http11AprProtocol" SSLEnabled="true"

maxThreads="150" scheme="https" secure="true"

clientAuth="false" sslProtocol="SSLv3"

SSLCertificateKeyFile="\${catalina.base}\\conf\\lobby3\\privatekey.txt"

SSLCertificateFile="\${catalina.base}\\conf\\raknet\\lobby3.raknet.com.txt"

/&gt;

In the text above, replace paths for SSLCertificateKeyFile and
SSLCertificateFile accordingly. SSLCertificateKeyFile is for the private
key (may be named privatekey.txt for example) and SSLCertificateFile is
for your website certificate, such as masterserver2.raknet.com.txt. You
do not need the intermediate key, if you were given one.

You can have multiple connectors if you want more than one website
hosted by this server. However, each connector will need a different
port.

Note that Skype also uses port 443. Either turn off Skype on this
computer, or change it to not use 443.\
<http://sharovatov.wordpress.com/2009/06/08/skype-blocking-80-and-443-ports/>

**Step 9: Start BigMemory\
(Used for Master Server 2 and Lobby3)**

Create a shortcut to
"C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin\\start-tc-server.bat" and place it
on the desktop.

To startup BigMemory:

Double the shortcut, and BigMemory should start. If you run that batch
from from the command prompt, you will need the –f option to tell it
where to find tc-config.xml. For example: start-tc-server.bat -f
"C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin\\tc-config.xml"

Wait a while, and you should get a console window that shows text
similar to this:

2013-07-28 10:15:52,522 INFO - Available Max Runtime Memory: 981MB\
2013-07-28 10:15:52,711 INFO - JMX Server started. Available at
URL\[service:jmx:jmxmp://0.0.0.0:9520\]\
2013-07-28 10:15:59,986 INFO - Becoming State\[ ACTIVE-COORDINATOR \]\
2013-07-28 10:16:00,003 INFO - Terracotta Server instance has started up
as ACTIVE node on 0.0.0.0:9510 successfully, and is now ready for work.\
Jul 28, 2013 10:16:00 AM
com.sun.jersey.server.impl.application.WebApplicationImpl \_initiate
INFO: Initiating Jersey application, version 'Jersey: 1.16 11/28/2012
02:09 PM'\
Jul 28, 2013 10:16:00 AM
com.sun.jersey.server.impl.application.DeferredResource
Config\$ApplicationHolder &lt;init&gt;\
INFO: Instantiated the Application class
com.terracotta.management.ApplicationTs

To shutdown BigMemory:

Run "C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin\\stop-tc-server.bat"

DO NOT JUST CLOSE THE CONSOLE WINDOW. YOU MAY LOSE DATA.

BigMemory has a management console

Create a shortcut to
“C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\tools\\management-console\\bin\\start-tmc.bat"
and place it on the desktop. Double click it. You should get text
similar to this:

Starting Terracotta Management Console at http://localhost:9889/tmc

2013-07-28 10:23:06.184:INFO::Redirecting stderr/stdout to
D:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\tools\\management-console\\logs\\2013\_07\_28.stderrout.log

Open a web browser, and in the URL field paste
<http://localhost:9889/tmc/>\
Ensure that the webpage loads. You will probably see “There are no
CacheManagers” which is fine.

To shutdown the management console, use
"C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\tools\\management-console\\bin\\stop-tmc.bat"

Data backups (Lobby3 only):

To make backups of your data (Lobby3 only) you can do so via the
management console under Administration / Backups

Backups are stored to C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin\\data-backup
with the directory name as the date.

To restore from a backup, so something similar to this:

del C:\\Users\\Administrator\\terracotta\\4.0.1\\server-data\\index\
copy
C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin\\data-backup\\backup.20130624.170502\\index
C:\\Users\\Administrator\\terracotta\\4.0.1\\server-data\\index\
del C:\\Users\\Administrator\\terracotta\\4.0.1\\server-data\\objectdb\
copy
C:\\bigmemory-max-4.0.1\\server\\bin\\data-backup\\backup.20130624.170502\\data\\objectdb
C:\\Users\\Administrator\\terracotta\\4.0.1\\server-data\\objectdb

I am not sure how to make automatic backups at this time, although I
know it is possible.

This same process can be used to load a backup onto another computer, in
case you need to migrate your data.

**Step 10: Start Apache Tomcat\
(Used for Master Server 2 and Lobby3)**

To startup Apache Tomcat

Create a shortcut to "C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.39\\bin\\startup.bat" and
paste it on your desktop. Be sure BigMemory is already running. Double
click your new shortcut. A lot of text will scroll off the screen. This
text should show on startup:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,){width="624"
height="359"}\
**Starting up**

\
\

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="624"
height="359"} **Loaded successfully**

Errors are easy to miss, so be careful the first time you run that
nothing shows up looking like an error

Test localhost

You should be able to go to <http://localhost/> in your webbrowser and
see whatever page you set it to in your &lt;Host&gt; section in
server.xml for Apache Tomcat.

Shutting down Apache Tomcat

Use "C:\\apache-tomcat-7.0.37\\bin\\shutdown.bat" do not just close the
window.\
Always shutdown Tomcat this way, and wait for the console window to
close, before shutting down BigMemory, to avoid data loss.

Setup DNS

Search for DNS hosting if you do not know how to do this. If you have a
webpage already, you might be able to set it up in the control panel

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,){width="624"
height="278"}

Set the DNS entry to the static IP address of your server

Test remote

If you set a host name other than localhost (that is, you set HOST
name=www.masterserver2.raknet.com), you should be able to visit that URL
in a webbrowser once you have setup the corresponding DNS entry.

\

**Step 11: Run NAT Punchthrough / NAT Type detection**

Download RakNet\
<http://www.raknet.com/download.html>

Install Visual Studio Express if you do not have it already\
<http://www.microsoft.com/visualstudio/eng/downloads#d-express-windows-desktop>

Build

Open RakNet\_VS2008.sln, convert, build the project NATCompleteServer.
Right click NATCompleteServer and Set as Startup Project if it was not
already.

Run

Go to Debug / Start Debugging to run NATCompleteServer. If you want a
port other than the default, pass this on the command line.
